%N A390112 Smallest exponent b >= 2 such that the absolute value of the alternating 3-digit block sum of n^b equals n; 0 if none.
%C A390112 Let S_3(x) be the absolute value of the alternating sum of base-1000 digits of x.
%C A390112 Define a(n) as the smallest b >= 2 with S_3(n^b) = n; if no such b exists, set a(n) = 0.
%C A390112 Conjectured to exist for all n that are not powers of 1000, for which S_3(1000^b) = 1 for all b.
%H A390112 Pieter Post, <a href="/A390112/b390112.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a>
%F A390112 a(n) = min_{b >= 2 | S_3(n^b) = n} or 0 if no such b exists, where S_3(x) = abs(Sum_{k>=0} (-1)^k * d_k), where x = Sum_{k>=0} d_k * 1000^k, 0 <= d_k < 1000.
%F A390112 a(1000^k) = 0 for k > 0.
%e A390112 a(10) = 4 since 10^4 = 10000 => |10 - 000| = 10.
%e A390112 a(14) = 6 since 14^6 = 7529536 => |7 - 529 + 536| = 14.
%e A390112 a(22) = 4 since 22^4 = 234256 => |234 - 256| = 22.
%o A390112 (Python)
%o A390112 from itertools import count
%o A390112 from sympy.ntheory import digits
%o A390112 def a(n):
%o A390112     if n > 1 and (s:=str(n)) == '1'+'0'*(len(s)//3*3): return 0
%o A390112     return next(b for b in count(2) if n==abs(sum(-d if i&1 else d for i, d in enumerate(map(int, digits(n**b, 1000)[1:])))))
%o A390112 print([a(n) for n in range(63)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Oct 25 2025
